<p>The <b>rod</b>, <b>perch</b>, or <b>pole</b> (sometimes also <b>lug</b>)=
 is a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Surveying" title=3D"Surveyin=
g">surveyor's</a> tool<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Connections_1-0" class=3D"referen=
ce"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rod_(unit)#cite_note-Connectio=
ns-1"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>1<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]<=
/span></a></sup> and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Unit_of_lengt=
h" title=3D"Unit of length">unit of length</a> of various historical defini=
tions. In <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Imperial_units" title=3D=
"Imperial units">British imperial</a> and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.o=
rg/wiki/United_States_customary_units" title=3D"United States customary uni=
ts">US customary units</a>, it is defined as <link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-i=
nline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r1154941027"><span class=3D"fra=
c">16<span class=3D"sr-only">+</span><span class=3D"num">1</span>=E2=81=84<=
span class=3D"den">2</span></span> <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki=
/Foot_(unit)" title=3D"Foot (unit)">feet</a>, equal to exactly <link rel=3D=
"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r1154941027">=
<span class=3D"frac"><span class=3D"num">1</span>=E2=81=84<span class=3D"de=
n">320</span></span> of a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mile" ti=
tle=3D"Mile">mile</a>, or <link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=
=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r1154941027"><span class=3D"frac">5<span class=
=3D"sr-only">+</span><span class=3D"num">1</span>=E2=81=84<span class=3D"de=
n">2</span></span> <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Yard" title=3D"=
Yard">yards</a> (a quarter of a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Su=
rveyor%27s_chain" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Surveyor's chain">surveyor=
's chain</a>), and is exactly 5.0292 meters. The rod is useful as a unit of=
 length because integer multiples of it can form one <a href=3D"https://en.=
wikipedia.org/wiki/Acre" title=3D"Acre">acre</a> of square measure (area). =
The 'perfect acre'<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Connections0_2-0" class=3D"reference"=
><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rod_(unit)#cite_note-Connections0=
-2"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>2<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</s=
pan></a></sup> is a rectangular area of 43,560 square feet, bounded by side=
s 660 feet (a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Furlong" title=3D"Fu=
rlong">furlong</a>) long and 66 feet (a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org=
/wiki/Chain_(unit)" title=3D"Chain (unit)">chain</a>) wide (220 yards by 22=
 yards) or, equivalently, 40 rods by 4 rods. An acre is therefore 160 squar=
e rods or 10 square chains.
</p><p>The name <i>perch</i> derives from the <a href=3D"https://en.wikiped=
ia.org/wiki/Ancient_Roman_units_of_measurement" title=3D"Ancient Roman unit=
s of measurement">Ancient Roman unit</a>, the <i><a href=3D"https://en.wiki=
pedia.org/wiki/Pertica_(unit)" title=3D"Pertica (unit)">pertica</a></i>.
The measure also has a relationship with the military <a href=3D"https://en=
.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pike_(weapon)" title=3D"Pike (weapon)">pike</a> of abou=
t the same size. Both measures<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Connections_1-1" class=3D=
"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rod_(unit)#cite_note-C=
onnections-1"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>1<span class=3D"cite-bra=
cket">]</span></a></sup> date from the sixteenth century,<sup id=3D"cite_re=
f-Connections2_3-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org=
/wiki/Rod_(unit)#cite_note-Connections2-3"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</=
span>3<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> when the pike was sti=
ll utilized in national armies. The tool has been supplanted, first by <a h=
ref=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tape_measure" title=3D"Tape measure">s=
teel tapes</a> and later by electronic tools such as surveyor lasers and op=
tical target devices for surveying lands. In dialectal English, the term <i=
>lug</i> has also been used, although the <i><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedi=
a.org/wiki/Oxford_English_Dictionary" title=3D"Oxford English Dictionary">O=
xford English Dictionary</a></i> states that this unit, while usually of <l=
ink rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r11=
54941027"><span class=3D"frac">16<span class=3D"sr-only">+</span><span clas=
s=3D"num">1</span>=E2=81=84<span class=3D"den">2</span></span> feet, may al=
so be of 15, 18, 20, or 21 feet.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-bonten_4-0" class=3D"re=
ference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rod_(unit)#cite_note-bont=
en-4"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>4<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]<=
/span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-dict-lug_5-0" class=3D"reference"><a hr=
ef=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rod_(unit)#cite_note-dict-lug-5"><span =
class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>5<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></=
sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-OED-lug_6-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https:/=
/en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rod_(unit)#cite_note-OED-lug-6"><span class=3D"cite-=
bracket">[</span>6<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>In the United States until 1 January 2023, the rod was often defined=
 as 16.5 US survey feet, or approximately 5.029&nbsp;210&nbsp;058&nbsp;m.<s=
up id=3D"cite_ref-7" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.or=
g/wiki/Rod_(unit)#cite_note-7"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>7<span =
class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
