r_Aertsen" title=3D"Pieter Aertsen">Pieter Aertsen</a>'s painting <i><a hre=
f=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/A_Meat_Stall_with_the_Holy_Family_Giving=
_Alms" title=3D"A Meat Stall with the Holy Family Giving Alms">A Meat Stall=
 with the Holy Family Giving Alms</a></i> reads in <a href=3D"https://en.wi=
kipedia.org/wiki/Flemish_dialects" title=3D"Flemish dialects">Flemish</a>: =
"behind here are 154 rods of land for sale immediately, either by the rod a=
ccording to your convenience or all at once".</figcaption></figure>
<p>In England, the perch was officially discouraged in favour of the rod as=
 early as the 15th century;<sup id=3D"cite_ref-8" class=3D"reference"><a hr=
ef=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rod_(unit)#cite_note-8"><span class=3D"=
cite-bracket">[</span>8<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup =
class=3D"noprint Inline-Template noprint noexcerpt Template-Fact" style=3D"=
white-space:nowrap;">[<i><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wikipedia=
:NOTRS" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Wikipedia:NOTRS"><span title=3D"More=
 detail needed - There are many editions of Encyclop=C3=A6dia Britannica an=
d each edition has multiple articles. (July 2013)">better&nbsp;source&nbsp;=
needed</span></a></i>]</sup> however, local customs maintained its use. In =
the 13th century, perches were variously recorded in lengths of 18 feet (5.=
49&nbsp;m), 20 feet (6.1&nbsp;m), 22 feet (6.71&nbsp;m) and 24 feet (7.32&n=
bsp;m); and even as late as 1820, a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wik=
i/House_of_Commons_of_the_United_Kingdom" title=3D"House of Commons of the =
United Kingdom">House of Commons</a> report notes lengths of <link rel=3D"m=
w-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r1154941027"><s=
pan class=3D"frac">16<span class=3D"sr-only">+</span><span class=3D"num">1<=
/span>=E2=81=84<span class=3D"den">2</span></span> feet (5.03&nbsp;m), 18 f=
eet (5.49&nbsp;m), 21 feet (6.4&nbsp;m), 24 feet (7.32&nbsp;m), and even 25=
 feet (7.62&nbsp;m).<sup id=3D"cite_ref-9" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"h=
ttps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rod_(unit)#cite_note-9"><span class=3D"cite-br=
acket">[</span>9<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> In <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ireland" title=3D"Ireland">Ireland</a>, a=
 perch was standardized at 21 feet (6.4&nbsp;m), making an Irish chain, <a =
href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Furlong" title=3D"Furlong">furlong</a=
> and mile proportionately longer by 27.27% than the "standard" English mea=
sure.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-10" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wiki=
pedia.org/wiki/Rod_(unit)#cite_note-10"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</spa=
n>10<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>Until English King <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Henry_VI=
II_of_England" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Henry VIII of England">Henry =
VIII</a> seized the lands of the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/R=
oman_Catholic_Church" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Roman Catholic Church"=
>Roman Catholic Church</a> in 1536,<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Connections_1-2" cla=
ss=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rod_(unit)#cite_n=
ote-Connections-1"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>1<span class=3D"cit=
e-bracket">]</span></a></sup> modern land measures were essentially unknown=
.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Connections_1-3" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https:=
//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rod_(unit)#cite_note-Connections-1"><span class=3D"=
cite-bracket">[</span>1<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> Inst=
ead a narrative system of landmarks and lists was used. Henry wanted to rai=
se even more funds for his wars than he'd seized directly from church prope=
rty (he'd also assumed the debts of the monasteries<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Conn=
ections_1-4" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/R=
od_(unit)#cite_note-Connections-1"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>1<s=
pan class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>), and as <a href=3D"https://e=
n.wikipedia.org/wiki/James_Burke_(science_historian)" title=3D"James Burke =
(science historian)">James Burke</a> writes and quotes in the book <i><a hr=
ef=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Connections_(book)" class=3D"mw-redirec=
t" title=3D"Connections (book)">Connections</a></i> that the English monk <=
a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Richard_Benese" title=3D"Richard Be=
nese">Richard Benese</a> "produced a book on how to survey land using the s=
imple tools of the time, a rod with cord carrying knots at certain interval=
s, waxed and resined against wet weather." Benese poetically described the =
measure of an acre in terms of a perch:<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Connections2_3-1=
" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rod_(unit)#c=
ite_note-Connections2-3"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>3<span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<blockquote class=3D"templatequote"><p>an acre bothe of woodlande, also of =
fyldlande [heath] is always forty perches in length, and four perches in br=
eadth, though an acre of woodlande be more in quantitie [value, i.e. was mo=
re valued commercially] than an acre of fyldelande</p></blockquote>
<p>The practice of using surveyor's chains, and perch-length rods made into=
 a detachable stiff chain, came about a century later when iron was a more =
plentiful and common material. A <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/C=
hain_(unit)" title=3D"Chain (unit)">chain</a> is a larger <a href=3D"https:=
//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Units_of_measurement" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=
=3D"Units of measurement">unit</a> of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w=
iki/Length" title=3D"Length">length</a> measuring 66 <a href=3D"https://en.=
wikipedia.org/wiki/Foot_(unit)" title=3D"Foot (unit)">feet</a> (20.1168&nbs=
p;<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Metre" title=3D"Metre">m</a>), o=
r 22 <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Yard_(unit_of_length)" class=
=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Yard (unit of length)">yards</a>, or 100 <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Link_(unit)" title=3D"Link (unit)">links<=
/a>,<sup id=3D"cite_ref-11" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikip=
edia.org/wiki/Rod_(unit)#cite_note-11"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span=
>11<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> or 4 rods (20.1168 <a hr=
ef=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Meter" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"M=
eter">meters</a>). There are 10 chains or 40 rods in a furlong (eighth-mile=
), and so 80 chains or 320 rods in one <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/=
wiki/Statute_mile" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Statute mile">statute mil=
e</a> (1760 yards, 1609.344 m, 1.609344 <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org=
/wiki/Kilometer" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Kilometer">km</a>); the def=
inition of which was <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Act_against_C=
onverting_of_Great_Houses_into_Several_Tenements_and_for_Restraint_of_Inmat=
es_and_Inclosures_in_and_near_about_the_City_of_London_and_Westminster" cla=
ss=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Act against Converting of Great Houses into Sev=
eral Tenements and for Restraint of Inmates and Inclosures in and near abou=
t the City of London and Westminster">legally set in 1593</a> and populariz=
ed by Royal surveyor (called the 'sworn viewer'<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Connecti=
ons3_12-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rod=
_(unit)#cite_note-Connections3-12"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>12<=
span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>) <a href=3D"https://en.wikip=
edia.org/wiki/John_Ogilby" title=3D"John Ogilby">John Ogilby</a> only after=
 the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Great_Fire_of_London" title=
=3D"Great Fire of London">Great Fire of London</a> (1666).
</p><p>An <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Acre" title=3D"Acre">acr=
e</a> is defined as the area of 10 square chains (that is, an area of one c=
hain by one furlong), and derives from the shapes of new-tech plows<sup id=
=3D"cite_ref-Connections0_2-1" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wi=
kipedia.org/wiki/Rod_(unit)#cite_note-Connections0-2"><span class=3D"cite-b=
racket">[</span>2<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> and the de=
sire to quickly survey seized church lands into a quantity of squares for q=
uick sales<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Connections2_3-2" class=3D"reference"><a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rod_(unit)#cite_note-Connections2-3"><spa=
n class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>3<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a>=
</sup> by Henry VIII's agents; buyers simply wanted to know what they were =
buying whereas Henry was raising cash for wars against Scotland and France.=
<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Connections2_3-3" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https:=
//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rod_(unit)#cite_note-Connections2-3"><span class=3D=
"cite-bracket">[</span>3<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> Con=
sequently, the surveyor's chain and surveyor rods or poles (the perch) have=
 been used for several centuries in Britain and in many other countries inf=
luenced by British practices such as North America and Australia. By the ti=
me of the industrial revolution and the quickening of land sales, canal and=
 railway surveys, et al. Surveyor rods such as used by <a href=3D"https://e=
n.wikipedia.org/wiki/George_Washington" title=3D"George Washington">George =
Washington</a> were generally made of dimensionally stable metal=E2=80=94se=
mi-flexible drawn wrought iron linkable bar stock (not steel), such that th=
e four folded elements of a chain were easily transportable through brush a=
nd branches when carried by a single man of a surveyor's crew. With a direc=
t ratio to the length of a surveyor's chain and the sides of both an acre a=
nd a square (mile), they were common tools used by surveyors, if only to la=
y out a known plottable baseline in rough terrain thereafter serving as the=
 reference line for instrumental (<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/=
Theodolite" title=3D"Theodolite">theodolite</a>) <a href=3D"https://en.wiki=
pedia.org/wiki/Triangulation" title=3D"Triangulation">triangulations</a>.
</p><p>The rod as a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Surveying" tit=
le=3D"Surveying">survey</a> measure was standardized by <a href=3D"https://=
en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Edmund_Gunter" title=3D"Edmund Gunter">Edmund Gunter<=
/a> in England in 1607 as a quarter of a chain (of 66 feet (20.12&nbsp;m)),=
 or <link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyl=
es:r1154941027"><span class=3D"frac">16<span class=3D"sr-only">+</span><spa=
n class=3D"num">1</span>=E2=81=84<span class=3D"den">2</span></span> feet (=
5.03&nbsp;m) long.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"In_ancient_cultures">In anc=
ient cultures</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsect=
ion-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=
=3DRod_(unit)&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D2" title=3D"Edit section: In =
ancient cultures"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracke=
t">]</span></span></div>
<p>The <b>perch</b> (<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pertica_(unit=
)" title=3D"Pertica (unit)">pertica</a>) as a <a href=3D"https://en.wikiped=
ia.org/wiki/Ancient_Roman_units_of_measurement" title=3D"Ancient Roman unit=
s of measurement">lineal measure in Rome</a> (also <i>decempeda</i>) was 10=
 Roman feet (2.96 metres), and in <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/=
France" title=3D"France">France</a> varied from 10 feet (<i>perche romanie<=
/i>) to 22 feet (<i>perche d'arpent</i>=E2=80=94apparently <link rel=3D"mw-=
deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r1154941027"><spa=
n class=3D"frac"><span class=3D"num">1</span>=E2=81=84<span class=3D"den">1=
0</span></span> of "the range of an arrow"=E2=80=94about 220&nbsp;ft (67&nb=
sp;m)). To confuse matters further, by ancient Roman definition, an arpent =
equalled 120 Roman feet. The related unit of square measure was the <i>scru=
pulum</i> or <i>decempeda quadrata</i>, equivalent to about 8.76&nbsp;m<sup=
>2</sup> (94.3&nbsp;sq&nbsp;ft).<sup id=3D"cite_ref-smith_13-0" class=3D"re=
ference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rod_(unit)#cite_note-smit=
h-13"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>13<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]=
</span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"In_continental_Europe">In c=
ontinental Europe</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-edit=
section-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?ti=
tle=3DRod_(unit)&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D3" title=3D"Edit section: =
In continental Europe"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-b=
racket">]</span></span></div>
<figure class=3D"mw-halign-right" typeof=3D"mw:File/Thumb"><a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:M%C3%BCnster,_Historisches_Rathaus,_Preussisc=
he_halbe_Ruthe_--_2017_--_9783_(crop).jpg" class=3D"mw-file-description"><i=
mg src=3D"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/9/91/M%C3%BC=
nster%2C_Historisches_Rathaus%2C_Preussische_halbe_Ruthe_--_2017_--_9783_%2=
8crop%29.jpg/330px-M%C3%BCnster%2C_Historisches_Rathaus%2C_Preussische_halb=
e_Ruthe_--_2017_--_9783_%28crop%29.jpg" decoding=3D"async" width=3D"300" he=
ight=3D"100" class=3D"mw-file-element" data-file-width=3D"5013" data-file-h=
eight=3D"1671"></a><figcaption>A standard at the City Hall in <a href=3D"ht=
tps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/M%C3%BCnster" title=3D"M=C3=BCnster">M=C3=BCnst=
er</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Germany" title=3D"Germany"=
>Germany</a>, from 1816; the bar shown is one "Prussian Half Rod" (1.883&nb=
sp;m) long.</figcaption></figure>
<p>Units comparable to the perch, pole or rod were used in many European co=
untries, with names that include <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/F=
rench_language" title=3D"French language">French</a>: <i lang=3D"fr">perche=
</i> and <i>canne</i>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/German_lang=
uage" title=3D"German language">German</a>: <i lang=3D"de">Ruthe</i>, <a hr=
ef=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Italian_language" title=3D"Italian lang=
uage">Italian</a>: <i lang=3D"it">canna</i> and <i>pertica</i>, <a href=3D"=
https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Polish_language" title=3D"Polish language">Po=
lish</a>: <i lang=3D"pl">pr=C4=99t</i> and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.=
org/wiki/Spanish_language" title=3D"Spanish language">Spanish</a>: <i lang=
=3D"es">canna</i>. They were subdivided in many different ways, and were of=
 many different lengths.
</p>
