<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"In_Britain_and_Ireland">In =
Britain and Ireland</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-ed=
itsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?=
title=3DRod_(unit)&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D4" title=3D"Edit section=
: In Britain and Ireland"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsectio=
n-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<figure class=3D"mw-default-size" typeof=3D"mw:File/Thumb"><a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Gortavaura_-_geograph.org.uk_-_1258792.jpg" c=
lass=3D"mw-file-description"><img src=3D"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikip=
edia/commons/thumb/4/4d/Gortavaura_-_geograph.org.uk_-_1258792.jpg/250px-Go=
rtavaura_-_geograph.org.uk_-_1258792.jpg" decoding=3D"async" width=3D"250" =
height=3D"167" class=3D"mw-file-element" data-file-width=3D"640" data-file-=
height=3D"427"></a><figcaption>Land for sale in Gortavaura, <a href=3D"http=
s://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/County_Galway" title=3D"County Galway">County Gal=
way</a>, Ireland: the area is 48 acres, 3 <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.o=
rg/wiki/Rood_(unit)" title=3D"Rood (unit)">roods</a> and 29 perches. In met=
ric units, this is 19.8 <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hectares" =
class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Hectares">hectares</a>.</figcaption></figure=
>
<p>In England, the rod or perch was first defined in law by the <a href=3D"=
https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Composition_of_Yards_and_Perches" title=3D"Co=
mposition of Yards and Perches">Composition of Yards and Perches</a>, one o=
f the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Statutes_of_uncertain_date" =
title=3D"Statutes of uncertain date">statutes of uncertain date</a> from th=
e late 13th to early 14th centuries: <i>tres pedes faciunt ulnam, quinque u=
lne &amp; dimidia faciunt perticam</i> (three feet make a yard, five and a =
half yards make a perch).<sup id=3D"cite_ref-16" class=3D"reference"><a hre=
f=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rod_(unit)#cite_note-16"><span class=3D"=
cite-bracket">[</span>16<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>The length of the chain was standardized in 1620 by <a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Edmund_Gunter" title=3D"Edmund Gunter">Edmund Gunt=
er</a> at exactly four rods.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Taylor_17-0" class=3D"refer=
ence"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rod_(unit)#cite_note-Taylor-=
17"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>17<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</=
span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-Russell_18-0" class=3D"reference"><a hre=
f=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rod_(unit)#cite_note-Russell-18"><span c=
lass=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>18<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></=
sup> Fields were measured in acres, which were one chain (four rods) by one=
 furlong (in the United Kingdom, ten chains).<sup id=3D"cite_ref-dict-acre_=
19-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rod_(uni=
t)#cite_note-dict-acre-19"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>19<span cla=
ss=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>Bars of metal one rod long were used as standards of length when sur=
veying land. The rod was still in use as a common unit of measurement in th=
e mid-19th century, when <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Henry_Dav=
id_Thoreau" title=3D"Henry David Thoreau">Henry David Thoreau</a> used it f=
requently when describing distances in his work, <i><a href=3D"https://en.w=
ikipedia.org/wiki/Walden" title=3D"Walden">Walden</a></i>.<sup id=3D"cite_r=
ef-Thoreau1899_20-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.or=
g/wiki/Rod_(unit)#cite_note-Thoreau1899-20"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[<=
/span>20<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>In traditional <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Scottish_uni=
ts_of_measurement" title=3D"Scottish units of measurement">Scottish units</=
a>, a <i>Scottish rood</i> (<i>ruid</i> in <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.=
org/wiki/Scots_language" title=3D"Scots language">Lowland Scots</a>, <i>r=
=C3=B2d</i> in <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Scottish_Gaelic" ti=
tle=3D"Scottish Gaelic">Scottish Gaelic</a>), also <i><a href=3D"https://en=
.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fall_(Scots)" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Fall (Scot=
s)">fall</a></i> measures 222 inches (6 <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org=
/wiki/Ell" title=3D"Ell">ells</a>).<sup id=3D"cite_ref-21" class=3D"referen=
ce"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rod_(unit)#cite_note-21"><span=
 class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>21<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a>=
</sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Modern_use">Modern use</h2>=
<span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</sp=
an><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DRod_(unit)&amp;a=
ction=3Dedit&amp;section=3D5" title=3D"Edit section: Modern use"><span>edit=
</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>The rod was phased out as a legal unit of measurement in the United King=
dom as part of a ten-year metrication process that began on 24 May 1965.<su=
p id=3D"cite_ref-dti_22-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipe=
dia.org/wiki/Rod_(unit)#cite_note-dti-22"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</s=
pan>22<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<figure class=3D"mw-default-size" typeof=3D"mw:File/Thumb"><a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Indian_Ovens_(S)_2750.jpg" class=3D"mw-file-d=
escription"><img src=3D"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thum=
b/3/3b/Indian_Ovens_%28S%29_2750.jpg/250px-Indian_Ovens_%28S%29_2750.jpg" d=
ecoding=3D"async" width=3D"250" height=3D"167" class=3D"mw-file-element" da=
ta-file-width=3D"4608" data-file-height=3D"3072"></a><figcaption>Sign near =
a historic site in <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Indiana" title=
=3D"Indiana">Indiana</a>, with its location given as "80 rods east", equiva=
lent to roughly 400&nbsp;m or <link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" hr=
ef=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r1154941027"><span class=3D"frac"><span class=
=3D"num">1</span>=E2=81=84<span class=3D"den">4</span></span>&nbsp;mile.</f=
igcaption></figure>
<p>In the United States, the rod, along with the chain, furlong, and statut=
e mile (as well as the survey inch and survey foot) were based on the pre-1=
959 values for <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/United_States_custo=
mary_units" title=3D"United States customary units">United States customary=
 units</a> of linear measurement until 1 January 2023. The <a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mendenhall_Order" title=3D"Mendenhall Order">Mende=
nhall Order</a> of 1893 defined the yard as exactly <link rel=3D"mw-dedupli=
cated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r1154941027"><span class=
=3D"frac"><span class=3D"num">3600</span>=E2=81=84<span class=3D"den">3937<=
/span></span> meters, with all other units of linear measurement, including=
 the rod, based on the yard. In 1959, an international agreement (the <a hr=
ef=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/International_yard_and_pound" title=3D"=
International yard and pound">international yard and pound</a> agreement), =
defined the yard as the fundamental unit of length in the Imperial/USCU sys=
tem, defined as exactly 0.9144 metres. However, the above-noted units, when=
 used in surveying, may retain their pre-1959 values, depending on the legi=
slation in each state. The <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/U.S._Na=
tional_Geodetic_Survey" title=3D"U.S. National Geodetic Survey">U.S. Nation=
al Geodetic Survey</a> and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Nationa=
l_Institute_of_Standards_and_Technology" title=3D"National Institute of Sta=
ndards and Technology">National Institute of Standards and Technology</a> h=
ave replaced the definition for the above-mentioned units by the internatio=
nal 1959 definition of the foot, being exactly 0.3048 meters.<sup id=3D"cit=
e_ref-23" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rod_=
(unit)#cite_note-23"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>23<span class=3D"=
cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-24" class=3D"reference"=
><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rod_(unit)#cite_note-24"><span cl=
ass=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>24<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></s=
up>
</p><p>Despite no longer being in widespread use, the rod is still employed=
 in certain specialized fields. In recreational <a href=3D"https://en.wikip=
edia.org/wiki/Canoe" title=3D"Canoe">canoeing</a>, maps measure <a href=3D"=
https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Portage" title=3D"Portage">portages</a> (over=
land paths where canoes must be carried) in rods; typical canoes are approx=
imately one rod long.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-canoe1_25-0" class=3D"reference"><=
a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rod_(unit)#cite_note-canoe1-25"><sp=
an class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>25<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></=
a></sup> The term is also in widespread use in the acquisition of <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pipeline_transport" class=3D"mw-redirect"=
 title=3D"Pipeline transport">pipeline</a> <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.=
org/wiki/Easement" title=3D"Easement">easements</a>, as the offers for an e=
asement are often expressed on a "price per rod".<sup id=3D"cite_ref-26" cl=
ass=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rod_(unit)#cite_=
note-26"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>26<span class=3D"cite-bracket=
">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>In the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/United_Kingdom" titl=
e=3D"United Kingdom">United Kingdom</a>, the sizes of <a href=3D"https://en=
.wikipedia.org/wiki/Allotment_(gardening)" title=3D"Allotment (gardening)">=
allotment</a> <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Garden" title=3D"Gar=
den">gardens</a> continue to be measured in square poles in some areas, som=
etimes being referred to simply as <i>poles</i> rather than <i>square poles=
</i>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-allot_27-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https:/=
/en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rod_(unit)#cite_note-allot-27"><span class=3D"cite-b=
racket">[</span>27<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>
In <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Vermont" title=3D"Vermont">Verm=
ont</a>, the default <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Right-of-way_=
(transportation)" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Right-of-way (transportati=
on)">right-of-way</a> width of state and town highways and trails is three =
rods 49&nbsp;ft 6&nbsp;in (15.09&nbsp;m).<sup id=3D"cite_ref-vermont_28-0" =
class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rod_(unit)#cit=
e_note-vermont-28"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>28<span class=3D"ci=
te-bracket">]</span></a></sup> Rods can also be found on the older legal de=
scriptions of tracts of land in the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wik=
i/United_States" title=3D"United States">United States</a>, following the "=
<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Metes_and_bounds" title=3D"Metes a=
nd bounds">metes and bounds</a>" method of land survey;<sup id=3D"cite_ref-=
shelton_29-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/=
Rod_(unit)#cite_note-shelton-29"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>29<sp=
an class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> as shown in this actual legal =
description of rural real estate: <link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style=
" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r1244412712"></p><blockquote class=3D"temp=
latequote"><p>LEGAL DESCRIPTION: Commencing 45 rods East and 44 rods North =
of Southwest corner of Southwest 1/4 of Southwest 1/4; thence North 36 rods=
; thence East 35 rods; thence South 36 rods; thence West 35 rods to the pla=
ce of beginning, Manistique Township, Schoolcraft County, Michigan.<sup id=
=3D"cite_ref-property_30-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikip=
edia.org/wiki/Rod_(unit)#cite_note-property-30"><span class=3D"cite-bracket=
">[</span>30<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup></p></blockquote=
>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Area_and_volume"><span clas=
s=3D"anchor" id=3D"Area"></span>Area and volume</h2><span class=3D"mw-edits=
ection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://e=
n.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DRod_(unit)&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;sectio=
n=3D6" title=3D"Edit section: Area and volume"><span>edit</span></a><span c=
lass=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>The terms <i>pole</i>, <i>perch</i>, <i>rod</i> and <i>rood</i> have bee=
n used as units of area, and <i>perch</i> is also used as a unit of volume.=
 As a unit of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Area" title=3D"Area"=
>area</a>, a <i>square perch</i> (the perch being standardized to equal <li=
nk rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r115=
4941027"><span class=3D"frac">16<span class=3D"sr-only">+</span><span class=
=3D"num">1</span>=E2=81=84<span class=3D"den">2</span></span> feet, or <lin=
k rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r1154=
941027"><span class=3D"frac">5<span class=3D"sr-only">+</span><span class=
=3D"num">1</span>=E2=81=84<span class=3D"den">2</span></span> yards) is equ=
al to a <b>square rod</b>, <link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=
=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r1154941027"><span class=3D"frac">30<span class=
=3D"sr-only">+</span><span class=3D"num">1</span>=E2=81=84<span class=3D"de=
n">4</span></span> square yards (25.29 <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/=
wiki/Square_metre" title=3D"Square metre">square metres</a>) or <link rel=
=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r115494102=
7"><span class=3D"frac"><span class=3D"num">1</span>=E2=81=84<span class=3D=
"den">160</span></span> acre. There are 40 square perches to a <a href=3D"h=
ttps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rood_(measurement)" class=3D"mw-redirect" titl=
e=3D"Rood (measurement)">rood</a> (for example a rectangular area of 40 rod=
s times one rod), and 160 square perches to an <a href=3D"https://en.wikipe=
dia.org/wiki/Acre" title=3D"Acre">acre</a> (for example a rectangular area =
of 40 rods times 4 rods). This unit is usually referred to as a <i>perch</i=
> or <i>pole</i> even though <i>square perch</i> and <i>square pole</i> wer=
e the more precise terms. <i>Rod</i> was also sometimes used as a unit of a=
rea to refer to a rood.
</p><p>However, in the traditional French-based system in some countries, 1=
 square <i>perche</i> is 42.21 square metres.
</p><p>As of August 2013, perches and roods are used as government survey u=
nits in <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jamaica" title=3D"Jamaica"=
>Jamaica</a>.<sup class=3D"noprint Inline-Template Template-Fact" style=3D"=
white-space:nowrap;">[<i><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wikipedia=
:Citation_needed" title=3D"Wikipedia:Citation needed"><span title=3D"This c=
laim needs references to reliable sources. (August 2024)">citation needed</=
span></a></i>]</sup> They appear on most property title documents. The perc=
h is also in extensive use in <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sri_=
Lanka" title=3D"Sri Lanka">Sri Lanka</a>, being favored even over the rood =
and acre in real estate listings there.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-31" class=3D"ref=
erence"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rod_(unit)#cite_note-31"><=
span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>31<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span>=
</a></sup> Perches were informally used as a measure in <a href=3D"https://=
en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Queensland" title=3D"Queensland">Queensland</a> <a hr=
ef=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Real_estate" title=3D"Real estate">real=
 estate</a> until the early 21st century, mostly for historical gazetted pr=
operties in older suburbs.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-32" class=3D"reference"><a hr=
ef=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rod_(unit)#cite_note-32"><span class=3D=
"cite-bracket">[</span>32<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Volume">Volume</h3><span cl=
ass=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a hr=
ef=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DRod_(unit)&amp;action=3D=
edit&amp;section=3D7" title=3D"Edit section: Volume"><span>edit</span></a><=
span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>A traditional unit of volume for stone and other masonry. A perch of mas=
onry is the volume of a stone wall one perch (<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-=
inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r1154941027"><span class=3D"fr=
ac">16<span class=3D"sr-only">+</span><span class=3D"num">1</span>=E2=81=84=
<span class=3D"den">2</span></span> feet or 5.03 metres) long, 18 inches (4=
5.7&nbsp;cm) high, and 12 inches (30.5&nbsp;cm) thick. This is equivalent t=
o exactly <link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:Templa=
teStyles:r1154941027"><span class=3D"frac">24<span class=3D"sr-only">+</spa=
n><span class=3D"num">3</span>=E2=81=84<span class=3D"den">4</span></span> =
cubic feet (0.92 cubic yards; 0.70 cubic metres; 700 litres).
</p><p>There are two different measurements for a perch depending on the ty=
pe of masonry that is being built:
</p>
<ol><li>A dressed stone work is measured by the <link rel=3D"mw-deduplicate=
d-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r1154941027"><span class=3D"=
frac">24<span class=3D"sr-only">+</span><span class=3D"num">3</span>=E2=81=
=84<span class=3D"den">4</span></span>-cubic foot perch (<link rel=3D"mw-de=
duplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r1154941027"><span =
class=3D"frac">16<span class=3D"sr-only">+</span><span class=3D"num">1</spa=
n>=E2=81=84<span class=3D"den">2</span></span> feet or 5.03 metres) long, 1=
8 inches (45.7&nbsp;cm) high, and 12 inches (30.5&nbsp;cm) thick. This is e=
quivalent to exactly <link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-=
data:TemplateStyles:r1154941027"><span class=3D"frac">24<span class=3D"sr-o=
nly">+</span><span class=3D"num">3</span>=E2=81=84<span class=3D"den">4</sp=
an></span> cubic feet (0.916667 cubic yards; 0.700842 cubic metres).</li>
<li>a brick work or rubble wall made of broken stone of irregular size, sha=
pe and texture, made of undressed stone, is measured by the (<link rel=3D"m=
w-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r1154941027"><s=
pan class=3D"frac">16<span class=3D"sr-only">+</span><span class=3D"num">1<=
/span>=E2=81=84<span class=3D"den">2</span></span> feet or 5.03 metres) lon=
g, 12 inches (30.5&nbsp;cm) high, and 12 inches (30.5&nbsp;cm) thick. This =
is equivalent to exactly <link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D=
"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r1154941027"><span class=3D"frac">16<span class=3D"=
sr-only">+</span><span class=3D"num">1</span>=E2=81=84<span class=3D"den">2=
</span></span> cubic feet (0.611111 cubic yards; 0.467228 cubic metres).<su=
p id=3D"cite_ref-33" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.or=
g/wiki/Rod_(unit)#cite_note-33"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>33<spa=
n class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup></li></ol>
